<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Natchez Trace Parkway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Natchez Trace Parkway</h2><p><i>Mississippi / Alabama / Tennessee, USA · NTP, Natchez MS to Nashville TN</i></p><p><b>715 km following an ancient Indian path. No trucks, no billboards, max 80 km/h.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>649 km (403 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>12–14 hrs end-to-end; ideally 2–3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Spring (mid-March–May, dogwood and redbud) and fall (October)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Deer (the dominant hazard), summer thunderstorms, lots of slow drivers (which is the point)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>850</td></tr></table><hr><p>444 miles of pure parkway driving — no commercial vehicles, no stoplights, no billboards, max 50 mph. It follows the original Natchez Trace, an ancient Indian path that became the main return route for Mississippi River boatmen who'd floated their goods downriver to Natchez and had to walk back to Nashville. The path predates writing in this region. Bandits, accidents, and disease made it 'the Devil's Backbone' in its 19th-century heyday. Park Service interpretive markers along the way; you can spend a whole day on any 100-mile section. Mile markers count from MP 0 in Natchez.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Mt Locust Inn</b> — Oldest standing structure on the Trace. Late-1700s 'stand' inn where boatmen slept on the dirt floor for 25¢.</li><li><b>Rocky Springs</b> — Ghost-town site of an 1860 town of 2,600 — yellow fever, soil exhaustion, and the boll weevil killed it. Old church remains.</li><li><b>Cypress Swamp</b> — Boardwalk loop through a bald cypress / tupelo swamp — Spanish moss, alligators, prothonotary warblers.</li><li><b>Tupelo</b> — Elvis Presley's birthplace (just off the parkway) and Park Service HQ for the Trace. Free visitor center museum.</li><li><b>Pharr Mounds</b> — Eight Native American burial mounds spread over 36 ha, built ~1–200 CE. Largely untouched.</li><li><b>Meriwether Lewis grave</b> — The Lewis &amp; Clark co-leader died here in 1809 from gunshot wounds — suicide or murder, still debated. Stone monument.</li><li><b>Jackson Falls</b> — 9 m cascade, 0.5 km steep paved trail to the base. Flow varies; best after rain.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
